ons under one umbrella group. Federation members are pet industry specialists and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">include groomers, pet boarders, pet retailers and manufacturers. We are the only organisation to represent all the different sectors of the pet industry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">combined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">member</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ship numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">around 1500 businesses, mostly small, medium</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-sized enterprises ranging from pet retailers, dog groomers, kennels &amp; catteries, manufacturers, wholesalers and professional services, which included colleges, publishers, dog walkers and pet sitters.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides a quality assura</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nce of businesses in the pet care sector: all members agree to adhere to our charters, representing best practice for the different sectors of the pet trade on joining the relevant association.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation is dedicated to promoting animal welfare within the pet industry and encouraging responsible pet ownership.  </span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center; text-indent:35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Keeping  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">rimates as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ets  </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Indus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">try</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ederation recognises that p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimates are intelligent animals that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">require specialist care in order to be properly cared for in captivity.  They are almost always social creatures (with a few species exceptions) and should not be kept alone.  Their particular husbandry demands and the need for significant amounts of menta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l and physical stimulation in captivity means the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">et Industry Federation is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not in favour of these animals being kept alone under normal circumstances and does not support the keeping of primates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">home environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation does </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wever </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support the private ownership of primates housed in appropriate conditions with quality husbandry and behavioural enrichment regimes.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eg. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where animals are kept in large indoor/outdoor enclosures as mated pairs or groups.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Current Guidelines and L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">egislation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation thinks that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DEFRA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ode of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ractice, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nimal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elfare </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ct and D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">angerous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ild </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nimal Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> combined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are more than sufficient to assure the welfare of animals.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However it may be worth considering that for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such a ‘demanding’ animal type it may be that licencing (outside of DWA)or a system of registering with the Local Authority  may be a potential option.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If licensing is an option then consideration must be paid to those carrying out the inspection process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and that inspectors must have a thorough knowledge and understanding of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">species in quest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion and that local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should have sufficient resources for adequate  enforcement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as we understand that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> compliance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> under the DWA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> low </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation believes the Government needs to remain aware of existing legislation and the practicalities of enforcement.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Implementing a Ban</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Animal Welfare </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a duty of care on all animal owners.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this is legislative protection for many different types of animal, and that specific exclusions on the ownership of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimates would be disproportionate and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unreasonable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would need to be an extremely strong argume</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt on public safety or welfare grounds for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Pet Industry Federation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to take the position of supporting a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">total </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ban.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In conclusion the Pet Industry Federation understands </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Primates require specific care to satisfy their needs in captivity. This however is not inherently different from requirement levels set out for other animals.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Pet Industry Federation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would not support an outright ban on the keeping of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rimates in c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aptivity where their welfare needs can be met but would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> restrictions on keeping Primates as pets , where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a pet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is defined as an individual animal or animals kept with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  household</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> situation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On animal welfare grounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Pet Ethics Group st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rongly advises its Pet Industry Federation members against selling any companion or pet primate to members of the general public and largely endorse the RSPCA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s statement on keeping primates as pets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">14 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol t